@node "Introduction" "AmySTP Manual: Introduction"
@next "Requirements"
@prev "Main"
    Over the last few years, information is transferred via electronic
computer networks. Data such as texts, lists and even files ARE posted
between users all over the world! Expensive and accurate systems provide the
average user such services.

    However, sometimes you want to send a file to someone else, but that
person is not able to receive files by others, just only plain text files.
If the file is plain ASCII, there is no problem, but what if the requested
file is @{b}binary@{ub}?

    A few utilities exist for that particular purpose; to allow the encoding
of binary files by using plain @{b}ASCII@{ub} files. The most known one is the @{b}UU
Encode@{ub} format, published by a user, some years ago. It is very popular,
although it has some limitations and dissadvantages. The most noticeable
dissadvantage is that such utilities, create output ASCII files MUCH bigger
that the original binary files. This limits the file-exchanges very much.

    Here's @{b}AmySTP@{ub} comes in! It's an alternative @{b}binary@{ub} to @{b}ASCII@{ub} encoder
which, by using special compression algorithms, can create output @{b}ASCII@{ub}
files with similar sizes to the original binary ones. @{u}Thus the user is able
to send bigger files via e-mail messages.@{uu}
@endnode

@node "Requirements" "AmySTP Manual: Requirements"
@next "Installation"
@prev "Introduction"
    To use AmySTP you need:

    @{b}- An AMIGA® computer (well...can't do without one :-) )
    - KickStart 2.04 or later
    - 256K RAM@{ub}

    Using AmySTP on bigger files may require more memory, but in any case,
memory usage is very little!
@endnode

@node "Installation" "AmySTP Manual: Installation"
@prev "Requirements"
    Installation of AmySTP is very simple. The package consists of two
executable files; AmyStpEncoder and AmyStpDecoder. You just have to copy
those files in your executable path (such as the C: directory).

    To use the program, you need to access the Shell. Open a Shell window
and type:

    AmyStpEncoder <parameters>
            to encode a file

    AmyStpDecoder <parameters>
            to decode a file


  See also  @{"Usage" link "Usage" 0}
@endnode

@node "Usage" "AmySTP Manual: AmySTP Usage"
@next "Usage.AmyStpEncoder"
@prev "Installation"
    Please select:

    @{"AmyStpEncoder" link "Usage.AmyStpEncoder" 0}       AmyStpEncoder Usage...
    @{"AmyStpDecoder" link "Usage.AmyStpDecoder" 0}       AmyStpDecoder Usage...
@endnode

@node "Usage.AmyStpEncoder" "AmySTP Manual: AmyStpEncoder Usage"
@next "Usage.AmyStpDecoder"
@prev "Usage"
    Usage of AmyStpEncoder is:

    AmyStpEncoder  @{b}[binary_infile]@{ub} @{b}[txt_outfile]@{ub} @{i}{-d=xx}@{ui}

 Explanation:

 @{b}binary_infile@{ub} is the name of the binary file to be encoded

 @{b}txt_outfile@{ub} is the name of the output ASCII file to be produced
             from the binary one

 Two more @{b}@{i}optional@{ub}@{ui} parameters exist:

 @{b}-d@{ub}  Specifies the length of each line in the output file produced. @{u}The@{uu}
     @{u}smaller it gets, the bigger the output file gets@{uu}. Default is 70.


  @{b}NOTE:@{ub}  From v1.6b the @{b}-l@{ub} parameter is no longer valid. The reason for
  it's removal was that 1) it produced incompatible files that the pc
  STP decoder did not recognize, 2) sometimes produced BIGGER files
  instead of smaller ones.

  Thanks to @{i}Theodore Hatzikostas@{ui} for pointing this out to me! :-)
@endnode

@node "Usage.AmyStpDecoder" "AmySTP Manual: AmyStpDecoder Usage"
@next "Usage"
@prev "Usage.AmyStpEncoder"
    Usage of AmyStpDecoder is:

    AmyStpDecoder  @{b}[txt_infile]@{ub}

 Explanation:

 @{b}txt_infile@{ub} is the name of the ASCII file to produced that will
            produce the binary one
@endnode

@node "Techstuff" "AmySTP Manual: Technical Information"
@next "Examples"
@prev "Usage"
    AmySTP uses a similar algorithm like the UU Encode utilities do.
However, to produce smaller output ASCII files, AmySTP utilizes ASCII
character codes in the range 32-255 (where UU Encode uses characters
32-127). This can cause some problems with system that do not use/provide
characters 128-255.

    This makes AmySTP useless if you want to transfer files via Internet
mail (altough there exist servers that do not have problems with this
characters - check to find out if you have one).

    Even if this limitation sounds terrific, AmySTP is useful. You can use
it to post files via FidoNet-compatible systems. These systems were designed
later than the Usenet/Internet ones, thus they permit the user to write with
characters beyond 127. Using AmySTP in such networks can lower the required
bandwidth extremely, so the telephone costs.

    Care must be taken with FidoNet networks, also: be sure that neither
your mail software (Off-Line Reader, Tosser) or your BBS does not crop ASCII
characters beyond character 128 (a few badly programmed PC BBS/Editors, such
as GEdit have problems). All Amiga BBS software is know to be working
perfectly!

    Following these simple rules, AmySTP will serve you well for a long
time, without problems!


  @{b}NOTE:@{ub} At this time of writing (17-12-95) AmySTP has been tested under
  Unix and Internet mail, and reported to work fine. The best way to
  find out is simply by creating a STP file and posting it to yourself!
  That way you'll know if your provider's system accepts STP encoded files.
@endnode

@node "Examples" "AmySTP Manual: Examples"
@next "Contacts"
@prev "Techstuff"
    @{u}Some examples of AmySTP usage:@{uu}

   - To encode a binary file @{i}file.ext@{ui} to an ASCII one @{i}file.txt@{ui}, type:

       AmyStpEncoder file.ext file.txt

   - To encode a binary file @{i}file1.ext@{ui} to an ASCII one @{i}file1.txt@{ui} with
     a line length of @{i}65@{ui} characters, type:

       AmyStpEncoder file1.ext file1.txt -d=65

   - To encode a binary file @{i}file2.ext@{ui} to an ASCII one @{i}file2.txt@{ui} with
     a line length of @{i}65@{ui} characters and with a @{i}suggested output file
     length of 5000 bytes@{ui} (original file2.ext size=4000bytes), type:

       AmyStpEncoder file2.ext file2.txt -d=65 -l=5000

   - To decode an ASCII STP file @{i}file.txt@{ui}, type:

       AmyStpDecoder file.txt
@endnode

